title: For Trade:  French MAS Model 1892 Lebel revolver
postcontent: I have a French military revolver made towards the end of WWI at the MAS (Manufacture d'armes de Saint-Étienne) chambered in 8mm Lebel. The 1892 revolver was the standard issue sidearm for officers in the French military during WWI, and most were re-issued to French pilots during WWII in case of crash or bailout over enemy territory. Contrary to most revolvers (and to the pleasure of southpaws) the cylinder swings to the right, the idea being the French officer would be on horse back, holding the gun and reins with his left hand as he re-loaded with his right. This particular example has a lot of "character;" it was pulled from a safe in the ashes of a house fire of a relative many years ago. It was gone through by a gunsmith to ensure safety and has been fired many times over the years since. Grips were replaced since the bottom of the originals were singed. Additionally the barrel was squibbed at some point (possibly during its service lifetime) and was replaced, although the original barrel (bulge and all!) is still with the gun, the replacement is dated 1921. I have no idea what it is worth, looking to trade with someone who will appreciate the history as much as I do. Not the prettiest girl at the party, but she dances just fine. Comes with 50 rounds of Fiocchi 8mm 111gr Lebel, and another 50 of once fired brass.

title: For Sale:  Ultra Rare Russian Bakelite AK-47 Mags
postcontent:
Hello all,

Real Russian Bakelite AK-47 7.62x39 caliber 30 round mags for sale. These are used 'Very Good' to 'Like New' with some imperfections like minor surface rust on the floor plate, follower and locking lugs from long term storage. The body is made of orange color Bakelite, which is a high strength polymer that does not dent or rust.  Some mags may have scratches, scuffing and wear, but many are like new. Condition will vary mag to mag and sold 'as is' but from what I have seen these are extremely nice in condition and most are like new. Some mags may have ink stamps and others do not,  some are proofed as Tula and some are Izhevsk, special selection is not available. Bakelite AK47 Mags are known for being rare and of excellent quality and functionality. They also weigh about 0.2 pounds less than regular steel AK-47 mags, saving you some total gear / gun weight when used. AK aficionados consider Russian Bakelite mags to be the highest quality mag ever produced for AK47 Rifles.

title: For Sale:  Russian Vepr 7.62x39 922r
postcontent:
I have for sale a new Russian Vepr, chambered in 7.62x39.  This rifle is produced in the molot factory in Russia, and is based off of the RPK, with a thicker, hammer forged, chrome-lined barrel, and a thicker receiver.  I've heard from different people that these rifles are currently banned from import, however, I don't have 100% confirmation on that.  It was however, very difficult for me to find one to purchase, and they don't seem to have gotten any easier to find as time as gone by.

When purchased, mine was in "sporterized condition" having a finished thumbhole stock, a welded on muzzle nut, and the ability to only accept 5-10 round factory magazines, which included two.  Aside from the original factory instruction manual, (translated into English from Russian, poorly) it also includes the AK cleaning kit, and AK cleaning rod.  The barrel length is 16" and the rifle is a Wolf Performance Arms style import, not a robinson arms import.  I have done the following to the rifle:

Added the Slant Adapter, this allows it to accept standard AK stocks.

Added the bullet guide, secured with red loctite: This allows standard AK 30 round magazines to feed.

Filed down the Magazine catch: This allows standard Ak 30 round magazines to actually lock into place, so that they may feed the rounds properly.

Added a black Magpul MOE AK stock, along with a .75" extended butt-pad

Added A US palm pistol grip.

Removed the welded muzzle nut, so that it will now accept standard AK 14x1 LH threaded muzzle devices.

Added a Slovak style muzzle break from bonesteel arms.

Added an ALG AKT trigger group https://algdefense.com/ak-trigger-akt.html

I have also purchased a AR style flash hider from CNC warrior.

As per law, this rifle requires four US made parts, these parts are the following: the buttstock, the trigger, the hammer, and the sear.  I have shot a little over a hundred rounds through the rifle, using brass cased ammunition, in order to make sure that the magazines I have properly feed, which they do.  The gun includes three 30 round magazines, two new Croatian magazines, and one surplus Romanian Magazines.  I am also including 500 rounds of Yugo Surplus M67 ammunition with a plastic ammo case.  This ammunition has mildly corrosive primers, but it is brass cased, and does not have a bi-metal jacket, so it is completely range safe.  It also includes a plano rifle case, as pictured.  I also still have all of the original wood furniture, and magazines.  

Truth be told, I do not actually want to sell this gun.  But I need to buy myself a car before winter really kicks in, and getting to work is more important that having a hell of a rifle.  If interested, please give me a call or text at 320-twonineeight-2101.  Thank you.  

PTP or PTC required
